definition.value: A C-glycosyl compound that is isoscoparin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a 6-sinapoylglucosyl residue.
An organosulfur compound with the formula RSO2SR.
A L-galactose 1-phosphate(2-) in which the anomeric center has beta-configuration.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is chrysoeriol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by an alpha-L-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-glucosyl moiety.
A 1,2-diglyceride with acyl groups at positions 2 and 3 of the sn-glycerol.
A carbohydrate acid anion that is the conjugate base of D-galactopyranuronic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 3-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the R-enantiomer of 2,3-dihydroxypropyl decanoate.
A 3-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the R-enantiomer of 2,3-dihydroxypropyl dodecanoate (glyceryl monolaurate).
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the S-enantiomer of  2,3-dihydroxypropyl dodecanoate (glyceryl monolaurate).

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 5-chlorosalicylic acid with the amino group of 2-chloro-4-nitroaniline. It is an oral anthelmintic drug approved for use against tapeworm infections.
A racemate that is composed of equal amounts of 1-acyl-sn-glycerol and 3-acyl-sn-glycerol.
A racemate that is composed of equal amounts of  1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol and 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is luteolin with a 6-O-beta-D-arabinopyranosyl-beta-D-glucopyranosyl entity attached at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol that has oleoyl and lauroyl as the 2- and 3-acyl groups respectively.
A rac-1,2-diglyceride that is composed of equal amounts of  1-lauroyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol and  2-oleoyl-3-lauroyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the S-enantiomer of 1-myristoyl glycerol.
A 3-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the R-enantiomer of 1-myristoyl glycerol.
A 1-monoglyceride with dodecanoyl (lauroyl) as the acyl group.
A N-sulfonylurea that is 2-(carbamoylsulfamoyl)-N,N-dimethylpyridine-3-carboxamide substituted by a 4,6-dimethoxypyrimidin-2-yl group at the amino nitrogen.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol that has  oleoyl and myristoyl as 2- and 3-acyl groups respectively.
A  rac-1,2-diglyceride composed of equal amounts of 1-myristoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol and 2-oleoyl-3-myristoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol that has hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) as the 1-acyl group.
A  rac-1-monoacylglycerol comprising equal amounts of 1-lauroyl-sn-glycerol and 3-lauroyl-sn-glycerol
A member of the class of cinnamamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of ferulic acid with the amino group of agmatine.
A carbohydrate acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-keto-3-deoxy-L-galactonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol with oleoyl as 2-acyl group and palmitoyl as the 3-acyl group.
A 1-monoglyceride that has decanoyl (capryl) as the acyl group.
A rac-1,2-diglyceride composed of equal amounts of 1-palmitoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol and  2-oleoyl-3-palmitoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol that has octadecanoyl (stearoyl) as the 1-acyl group.
A  rac-1-monoacylglycerol composed of equal amounts of 3-decanoyl-sn-glycerol and 1-decanoyl-sn-glycerol.
A carbohydrate acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-deoxy-L-threo-hex-2-ulopyranosonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 3-acyl-sn-glycerol that has octadecanoyl (stearoyl) as the 3-acyl group.
A trihydroxyflavone that is the 6'''-O-feruloyl derivative of isovitexin 2''-O-arabinoside.
A 1-monoglyceride that has stearoyl as the acyl group.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is apigenin with a 6-O-beta-D-arabinopyranosyl-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety attached at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A  rac-1-monoacylglycerol  composed of equal amounts of 3-stearoyl-sn-glycerol and  1-stearoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol that has oleoyl and stearoyl as the 2- and 3-acyl groups respectively.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isovitexin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A rac-1,2-diglyceride composed of equal amounts of 1-stearoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol and 2-oleoyl-3-stearoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the S-enantiomer of 1-monolinolein.
A 1-monoglyceride with tetradecanoyl (myristoyl) as the acyl group.
A 3-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the R-enantiomer of 1-monolinolein.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isovitexin substituted at positions 4 and 7 by beta-glucosyl 6-O-sinapoylglucosyl residues respectively
A  rac-1-monoacylglycerol that is composed of equal amounts of 1-linoleoyl-sn-glycerol and 3-linoleoyl-sn-glycerol.
A C-glycosyl compound that is luteolin substituted at positions 6 and 8 by alpha-L-arabinopyranosyl and beta-D-glucosyl residues respectively.
A rac-1-monoacylglycerol that is composed of equal amounts of 1-myristoyl-sn-glycerol and  3-myristoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1-monoglyceride that has octadecadienoyl (linoleoyl) as the acyl group.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and linoleoyl form the 2- and 3-acyl groups respectively.
A rac-1,2-diglyceride composed of equal amounts of  1-linoleoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol and  3-linoleoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol.
A  3-acyl-sn-glycerol where arachidonoyl is the 3-acyl group.
